1
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Your Royal Highness. Forgive me.

2
00:00:05,249 --> 00:00:05,958
Lawrence?

3
00:00:06,333 --> 00:00:07,583
He's always late.

4
00:00:07,833 --> 00:00:09,208
Does it deliberately, I'm sure.

5
00:00:11,541 --> 00:00:14,166
My lecture at the RGS overran horribly.

6
00:00:15,583 --> 00:00:16,708
You're in great demand.

7
00:00:17,375 --> 00:00:22,000
everyone wanting to have their photograph taken with you. It's most tiresome.

8
00:00:22,166 --> 00:00:24,208
Ha Ha Ha

9
00:00:24,625 --> 00:00:30,458
Ah, Philby, old man. Long time no see. I trust the Foreign Office is making full use of your talents.

10
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:32,000
Lawrence.

11
00:00:33,708 --> 00:00:35,375
And you must be Prince Faisal.

12
00:00:36,708 --> 00:00:39,166
Not finding England too chilly, I trust?

13
00:00:40,125 --> 00:00:42,791
On the contrary, the weather is most climate.

14
00:00:43,208 --> 00:00:45,250
Spoken like a true Englishman.

15
00:01:02,541 --> 00:01:12,083
Mark my words, there is a revolt brewing in Mesopotamia. We must honor the promise of self-government as laid out in the Anglo-French declaration.

16
00:01:12,500 --> 00:01:13,750
Wouldn't you agree, Philby?

17
00:01:14,916 --> 00:01:15,666
I would.

18
00:01:16,333 --> 00:01:17,500
Absolutely.

19
00:01:17,875 --> 00:01:23,875
And we must let Faisal bin Hussein govern Mesopotamia. He is, in my estimation, the finest Arab leader since Saladin.

20
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:25,250
If I may.

21
00:01:29,041 --> 00:01:33,208
No man commands more respect across Arabia than Prince Faisal's father, Abdulaziz Al Saud.

22
00:01:33,708 --> 00:01:35,625
Abdulaziz Al Saud.

23
00:01:35,625 --> 00:01:39,625
This I learned when I rode right into the heart of Hussein's territory.

24
00:01:41,625 --> 00:01:49,791
You may wonder how I could enter the kingdom of the Hejaz unannounced, with no invitation, like the sun in the sky as old Hussein protested.

25
00:01:51,583 --> 00:01:54,042
Because I traveled on the authority of Al Saud.

26
00:01:54,666 --> 00:01:57,208
We have no greater friend in the whole of Arabia.

27
00:01:58,708 --> 00:02:00,708
What do you see, Prince Faisal

28
00:02:02,583 --> 00:02:10,708
Is it true? Could your father, the Emir, one day be King of all Arabia?

29
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:22,000
I thought an Englishman never discussed politics over the dinner table.

30
00:02:30,624 --> 00:02:33,083
How's the restoration going?

31
00:02:33,208 --> 00:02:35,458
Never buy a castle, Montague.

32
00:02:36,541 --> 00:02:39,708
Gertrude Bell's most persuasive on the matter. You must read her report.

33
00:02:40,666 --> 00:02:42,041
He's keep avoiding me

34
00:02:42,875 --> 00:02:44,541
Wait until he's drunk his first whiskey.

35
00:02:52,625 --> 00:02:56,166
Your master has asked for mint tea. Would you be kind enough to show us how it is made?

36
00:02:57,125 --> 00:02:58,583
Of course.

37
00:02:59,375 --> 00:03:01,375
Over there.

38
00:03:15,708 --> 00:03:17,708
How is the dinner going?

39
00:03:18,791 --> 00:03:19,791
All good.

40
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:27,291
You simply don't have the resources to maintain control of Mesopotamia.

41
00:03:28,333 --> 00:03:37,041
Day after day, week after week, there is a continuance of this wasteful, miserable, sporadic warfare.

42
00:03:38,083 --> 00:03:39,083
yeah.

43
00:03:39,250 --> 00:03:42,208
Not a single friend in the press upon the subject.

44
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:45,291
Cradle of civilization and they can't afford the ink.

45
00:03:45,791 --> 00:03:48,416
Doesn't this remind you of being at home?

46
00:03:50,625 --> 00:03:53,291
The men discussing affairs of state.

47
00:03:53,375 --> 00:03:55,083
I feel most at home.

48
00:03:55,333 --> 00:04:02,666
Before you leave for Arabia, you must come to my club as my guest. The food there is excellent.

49
00:04:03,166 --> 00:04:05,291
I would like that very much, Lord Curzon.

50
00:04:08,416 --> 00:04:09,000
But 

51
00:04:10,375 --> 00:04:12,583
I hope we can have another meeting first.

52
00:04:13,958 --> 00:04:14,958
In private.

53
00:04:15,375 --> 00:04:17,375
by time you went back to the desert.

54
00:04:18,125 --> 00:04:21,291
What the bloody hell! You did that on purpose.

55
00:04:21,708 --> 00:04:23,041
No, it was an accident.

56
00:04:23,875 --> 00:04:26,875
Marzuq, apologize. Do something.

57
00:04:29,375 --> 00:04:32,125
I apologize most sincerely. He's still learning.

58
00:04:49,458 --> 00:04:51,041
Splendid evening your highness.

59
00:04:51,374 --> 00:04:52,083
yes.

60
00:04:52,291 --> 00:04:54,458
but not as good food as at the lisay palace

61
00:04:56,833 --> 00:04:58,083
please excuse me.

62
00:05:00,375 --> 00:05:01,291
Where's Marzuq.

63
00:05:01,625 --> 00:05:02,750
he's in the Stables.

64
00:05:36,416 --> 00:05:37,375
Marzuq.

65
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:47,000
I have failed you.

66
00:05:47,833 --> 00:05:52,250
No. We are brothers and between us not a drop of water must come.

67
00:06:10,333 --> 00:06:11,291
Forgive me.

68
00:06:13,166 --> 00:06:15,375
Remember. When we arrived in Plymouth

69
00:06:16,750 --> 00:06:17,916
I saw the huge ship.

70
00:06:19,166 --> 00:06:21,166
The might of the British Navy.

71
00:06:21,791 --> 00:06:23,250
a British Navy

72
00:06:24,333 --> 00:06:25,458
I felt so small.

73
00:06:26,500 --> 00:06:27,250
So in awe.

74
00:06:29,375 --> 00:06:31,166
Why should the British listen to me?

75
00:06:32,166 --> 00:06:33,541
A boy from the desert?

76
00:06:34,750 --> 00:06:37,708
Because you are Prince Faisal bin Abdulaziz.

77
00:06:39,083 --> 00:06:40,249
am I really.

78
00:06:41,083 --> 00:06:43,375
You are a prince amongst men.

79
00:06:50,958 --> 00:06:54,958
tell me something. was it  an accident when you spled the tea over Montague.

80
00:06:57,249 --> 00:07:00,249
No. I never liked that man.

81
00:07:05,583 --> 00:07:06,416
we are going home.

82
00:07:08,958 --> 00:07:09,833
We are lost.

83
00:07:11,500 --> 00:07:12,041
No.

84
00:07:13,125 --> 00:07:15,125
We are going back to our real home.

85
00:07:16,958 --> 00:07:18,041
to Arabia.

